text: Been excited for this ever since I heard about this film and Sandler in a dramatic performance. According to what I read, the directors, Benny and Josh Safdie, initially wrote this back in 2009, and did try to get Sandler back in 2012, but he initially turned it down. They also did not have the funding necessary for the film. Around that time, they were contacted by Robert Pattison, who wanted to work with them just based off the intriguing poster of their film "Heaven Knows What". After they met Pattison, they came up with Good Time just for him. After that success of the film, they were approached with numerous film offers, including a big-budget superhero flick, but turned them all down and got funding for this instead. Jonah Hill was initially considered, but then after reaching out to Sandler again, he decided to work on the film. Can not wait to see this!!

text: This movie isn‚Äôt for everyone but personally it was my favorite movie of the year without a doubt. I saw Good Time in high school and it made me wanna make movies, and I‚Äôm currently twenty and in film school. The Safdie‚Äôs are a massive influence on me both in terms of story and visual aesthetic (I shoot all of my films on 35mm or 16mm). My roommates and I drove like two hours (we live in Cambridge MA and the nearest showing was in RI) to see Uncut Gems and we both agreed that it was beyond worth it. My only advice would be that the film is not for mainstream viewers. It sucks but I highly doubt it‚Äôll get any Oscar nods despite receiving a lot of awards buzz because it‚Äôs not an epic by any means. I think most mainstream viewers would find the film really boring because most of the film is the characters interacting and arguing with one another over Adam Sandler‚Äôs character‚Äôs destructive behavior and there‚Äôs not a lot of action beyond that. That‚Äôs not to say the movie is a slow-burn, though, because the execution is everything. The camerawork, tone, and soundtrack make it a really chaotic and anxiety-inducing film and the ending took me completely by surprise. If you‚Äôre someone who isn‚Äôt into Star Wars, Marvel, screwball comedies, or more conventional Oscar fare, I highly recommend this film. Especially if you‚Äôre a cinephile or someone who wants to make movies. Just don‚Äôt go in expecting to be entertained, and certainly don‚Äôt go in with any of Adam Sandler ‚Äòs previous work in mind.

text: I really wanted to like this film, but there‚Äôs so much yelling that it just ends up being noise. I wanted to see Adam Sandler succeed as a gangster shiester. I‚Äôve liked A24 in the past, but this was just too much. The volume is cranked to 10 for most of the film and I left with a headache. Great concept of having the things Sandler was interacting with increase in volume with respect to his proximity vs the camera, but some things got too loud for too long. The part he‚Äôs thrown into a fountain felt like my ears were in a perpetual explosion. And it was just stressful for the entire ride, which made the sound dynamics even worse feeling. Stress and volume for 2 hours is a long time. I say conceptually, the movies pretty solid, but there‚Äôs too much going on in shouting, and the pacing is awkward as a result. There will be what feels like 10 minutes of shouting for little payoff for the verbosity and cursing involved. Exposition in natural increments was pretty great. Loved that it slowly revealed how in deep Sandler was. I‚Äôd give it a 2/10, my SO a straight up zero. I liked the grit, but it felt like it was trying to be hard to like. text: POSSIBLE SPOILER ALERT This movie didn't make me too anxious; he had it coming to him the entire time.  He was a piece of shit to everyone during the whole movie.  In that sense, I found the movie a tad childish; in that it seemed to expect the audience to sympathize with him and look past his flaws, just as he is blind to them.  Of course, the actual makers of the movie have deeper intentions: that shallow sympathy and forgiving of all his flaws, especially, for example, in light of the "true love" between him and the chick, made the ending all the more shocking and yet appropriate to the movie.  I enjoyed Joker far more than this movie.  I don't know if I rank either in the top tier of movies, but they are both at least pretty close.  This one felt better put together than the Joker, but the Joker felt more original.

text: Interesting how so many fans of this show are comparing it against the Joker when the plots were so different.  Even more interesting how the character of the Joker was so much stronger to go through such a life, than how Howard Ratner lies, cheats and endangers the lives of everyone around him all for money. A very common and predictable fast action movie plot with some great intense, on the edge of your seat scenes, especially the ending.  Both actors did a great job, but definitely can't compare how much more in depth and complicated the Joker's character was. Seems the Joker made many people uncomfortable bc it was based on the problems with mental health. Yet mental health issues effect anyone with a brain. And I think making people uncomfortable is what the show was trying to achieve.  The characters of a macho action thriller like this movie, even if the top of the line action movie, don't even compare to the character of the Joker if given proper attention which many again, are too uncomfortable to do. Good acting does not always go together with what some people think is a good or bad movie.  In fact most movies that had record budgets and brought the masses rarely ever won an Oscar or Golden Globe award for good reason; usually from a lack of written depth of character. It was definitely nice to see Adam Sandler play a more serious character for a change and he did get some justifiable award talk, but it was not comparable to the deep, complicated and uncomfortable character Joaquin Phoenix's plays as the Joker. The movie Rain Man was a 1988 movie and it also was about mental health that won many awards.  However it had more comedy to make people feel more comfortable watching. Funny how comfort, or fun. or excitement makes us believe a movie is better but in fact it's just a more enjoyable feeling it brings; very different than quality.

Ultimately this was a perfect character study and if anyone needed this role when it comes to the eyes of the audience it was Adam Sandler so that goes hand and hand, it was so hard not to condemn the film after seeing it though i didn‚Äôt feel hatred or stress, I felt it might be the necessary action but after a while even that thought went oblivious and I guess I accepted my fondness for it because after I left the theatre I kept wanting more as if it was a form of dopamine that made me appreciate it more so. I truly believe it will age like wine, the longer it‚Äôs out the the more I wanted partake into that problematic scenario again. Enough of me the Safdie‚Äôs are Geniuses everyone know already my bad to even mention any of this or  Good Times even, Despite the fact that they Should have received at least single ounce of recognition, no respect in the industry to be overlooking films like this even though they captivated the audience, the Safdies deserved more unfortunately there‚Äôs no award for underdogs. Never mind these events, There were a lot of good films out this year an Oscar was unlikely but this should have received a nomination at the very least. I know They had our nominations and in the way they still do have ours, realistically that holds more worth then a sentiment of a trophy, the price will  show valuable in onward time. That‚Äôs the uncut truth, a verity per se.   I can‚Äôt imagine reflecting back on this film in eras to come though I‚Äôm even more thrilled to see what‚Äôs yet come.
